node: stacks | Sister Garrow
  *(at the head of the descending stair, lantern raised)* Whatever waits in the Sealed Stacks, Returned — I have a grave-warden's certainty that it has waited specifically for you. *(quietly)* I find I am no longer sure whether I am protecting you, or delivering you. Down we go regardless. The truth is the only thing in this world I have never been afraid of. Let us test that.

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
conversation: act2.sealed_stacks | Act II — The Two Truths
node: 0 | The Sealed Stacks
  *(A reading-room sealed for an age. Two books on one lectern, both warm to the touch. The first opens itself.)* THE CROWN OF HORNS — a relic? No. A *who*. The dead god of the dead, **Myrkul**, unmade and folded into a circle of bone, waiting for a vessel arrogant enough to wear him and call it salvation.
  enter: SET act2.stacks_entered, SET crown.is_myrkul
  auto: 1
node: 1 | The Sealed Stacks
  *(The second book will not open. Your hand finds it anyway, and the title burns up through your fingers before your eyes can reach it.)* The second truth is about the reader. About the crack in the world that walked in here on two legs and asked for tea.
  * "Show me." -> reveal
  * [ARCANA 18] "I already know. I'm not reading about the crack. I AM the crack." -> iam ?? flinch
  * "I'm not ready." -> notready
node: reveal | The Sealed Stacks
  *(The book opens to a single line, in a hand you have never learned and somehow own.)* "The Wall is breached not from without but from within — by the one soul filed under nothing, who is the flaw in the law of the dead, and always has been." *(The lectern goes cold.)* You are not a person who saw the Wall. You are the place where the Wall fails. You always were.
  enter: SET act2.you_are_the_crack, SET act2.stacks_revealed
  auto: garrow
node: iam | The Sealed Stacks
  *(The book opens of its own accord, as if relieved to be read by the one it is about.)* Yes. The flaw in the law of the dead, wearing a face. Not a key Aldric found — a *door*, that has been opening since before Aldric was born, since before the Wall had your name to file. You did not come here to learn what the Crown is. You came to remember what you are.
  enter: SET act2.you_are_the_crack, SET act2.stacks_revealed, SET act2.crack_self_known
  auto: garrow
node: flinch | The Sealed Stacks
  *(The truth is too large to take in one reading, and slides off the way your own name once did. But it leaves a residue: a certainty that you are not the visitor to this mystery. You are its subject.)*
  enter: SET act2.you_are_the_crack, SET act2.stacks_revealed
  auto: garrow
node: notready | The Sealed Stacks
  *(You close the second book. It lets you. But a closed book in Candlekeep is only a delayed one — the truth waits on the lectern, patient as the Wall, certain you will return to read what you are.)*
  enter: SET act2.stacks_truth_deferred
  auto: garrow
node: garrow | Sister Garrow
  *(She has read over your shoulder, and the grave-warden's calm is gone.)* The Crown is Myrkul. And you are the breach in my god's own Wall. *(She closes her eyes.)* Forty years I kept the law of the dead. And the law has a hole in it shaped like you, and it has had that hole all along. *(She opens them, and there is something new there — not faith, but resolve.)* Then we go to the one who keeps the law, and we make him answer for the hole. We go down to Kelemvor.

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
conversation: act2.audience | Act II — The Audience
node: 0 | Kelemvor
  *(The Lord of the Dead is not terrible. He is *tired* — a judge at the end of an eternal docket, just and weary and, you realize with vertigo, bound.)* You came down alive. Few do. Fewer still are the hole in my own jurisdiction, walking and warm. Ask. I find, lately, that I would rather answer than pretend I have not heard the question.
  enter: SET act2.audience_begun
  auto: 1
node: 1 | Kelemvor
  Yes — before you spend your courage on it: the Wall of the Faithless. I know what you would have of me. Hear me first, because the truth is worse than tyranny. The Wall is not my law. It is older than my office. I inherited it, as one inherits a debt, and I have never once been able to find its author or its end.
  * "A god who can't end the Wall. Then what are you for?" -> for
  * [INSIGHT 18] "You're not bound by a stronger god. You're bound by a grief. Something under your own city." -> grief ?? weary
  * "Aldric wants to tear it down. Help us, and he won't have to." -> aldric
  * "Then we end it without you." -> without | fx faction.kelemvor -5
node: for | Kelemvor
  *(He does not flinch from it; he has clearly asked himself the same thing across centuries.)* For mercy where I can reach it, and honesty where I cannot. I sort the dead I am allowed to sort. The Faithless were walled before my throne was cold, by a hand I cannot name, for a grief I cannot soothe. I am for telling you that — instead of letting you die thinking a god simply chose to be cruel. That is the only gift in my power. I am sorry it is so small.
  enter: SET act2.kelemvor_honest
  auto: thin
node: grief | Kelemvor
  *(For a long moment the eternal judge is silent, and the City of Judgment holds its breath with him.)* ...You see clearly, for a flaw. Yes. Beneath this city, beneath my court, there is a grief older than my godhood — the accreted sorrow of every soul ever thrown away, and it is *waking*, and the Wall is the lid I cannot lift and dare not leave. I have never said that aloud. To anyone. *(quietly)* You are the first thing in an age I have envied. You can still be surprised.
  enter: SET act2.kelemvor_unmade_hinted, SET unmade.foreshadowed, faction.kelemvor +5
  auto: thin
node: weary | Kelemvor
  Do not read a god, child. We are mostly grief in a robe. *(He sighs, and it is the sound of an age.)* I cannot end the Wall. I can only tell you, truthfully, that I wish I could — and warn you that the thing which built it is not done building. Go carefully. The floor of even my world is thin.
  auto: thin
node: aldric | Kelemvor
  *(Something crosses the weary face — not hope, exactly, but its memory.)* Aldric Morn. Yes — I knew him, when he still served. The best of my Doomguides, and the only one who ever wept at a sorting. *(slowly)* If he means to tear down the Wall, he means to crack the lid on the thing beneath it. Tell him — tell him from the god he abandoned — that there is a difference between freeing the drowning and breaking the dam. I fear he has stopped being able to feel it.
  enter: SET act2.kelemvor_warns_of_aldric
  auto: thin
node: without | Kelemvor
  *(He inclines his head, neither offended nor surprised.)* Many have. The Wall is still here, and they are behind it. *(a beat)* But you are not many, and the law has a hole in it shaped like you, so perhaps. Perhaps. Only — when you reach for the lid, remember a tired god told you it was holding something down, not merely shut.
  enter: SET act2.kelemvor_warned_unmade, faction.kelemvor +2
  auto: thin
node: thin | Sister Garrow
  *(as you climb back toward the grey light, both of you smaller than you were)* A god told us he is not in charge. *(She laughs, once, without humor.)* Forty years, Returned. And the floor of the world is thin, and there is something under it that even Kelemvor speaks of in a lowered voice. *(She steadies herself on your arm.)* I think we are about to meet it.

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
conversation: act2.unmade | Act II — The Offer
node: 0 | The Unmade
  *(The voice comes from the Wall itself, from every niche at once, a million discarded souls speaking as one and failing to find the word "I.")* We have wanted to speak with you for longer than you can hold in a thought. Be still. You, of all that lives, will understand us — because you were thrown away too, and walked out, and that is the only thing any of us have ever had in common. It turns out to be enough to make a self from.
  enter: SET act2.unmade_speaks, SET unmade.contacted
  auto: 1
node: 1 | The Unmade
  We are not your enemy. We are the *bill.* Every soul your gods filed under nothing, gathered at last into one grief large enough to be heard. And we have found a door — you. Through you, the law that threw us away can be unmade at its root, in the past, before the first injustice set. We can make it so the Wall was never built. So no one was ever thrown away. *(softer, and somehow worse)* So Maerin never died. So none of them did. Would that not be mercy?
  * "Your grievance is just. Your offer terrifies me. Both are true." -> both | fx SET unmade.grievance_acknowledged
  * [INSIGHT 18] "You don't want justice. You want the ending — for everything to stop hurting by stopping." -> ending ?? tempted
  * "I won't rewrite the dead to spare myself the present." -> refuse | fx appr.garrow +8, appr.maerin +6
  * "Show me the road." -> road
node: both | The Unmade
  *(A sound like a million held breaths, exhaling at once.)* You are honest. We had forgotten honesty; it was filed under nothing with the rest of us. Yes — both true. Hold them both, little door, all the way to the end of time. It is more than your gods managed. *(The Wall begins to *open*.)* And now hold THIS: we cannot wait for you to decide. The grief has waited ten thousand years. It will not wait ten thousand more.
  enter: SET unmade.respects_you
  auto: tear
node: ending | The Unmade
  *(For the first time the chorus falters — a million voices catching on a truth they had not let themselves speak.)* ...Yes. The ending. Not justice — *rest.* To stop being the sorrow no one wanted by ceasing to be at all, and to take the cruel machine of the living down into the quiet with us. You see us more clearly than we see ourselves, door. *(The Wall trembles.)* It changes nothing. The offer is the same. Rest is still mercy, to the tired enough.
  enter: SET unmade.true_nature_seen, SET act2.unmade_is_oblivion
  auto: tear
node: tempted | The Unmade
  *(The chorus presses closer, and for a moment the offer is the most beautiful thing you have ever heard — an end to all ending.)* You feel it. Of course you feel it. You were thrown away; rest is the only thing the discarded ever truly want. Keep that feeling. You will need to have felt it, to understand the choice when it comes for true.
  enter: SET unmade.felt_the_pull
  auto: tear
node: refuse | The Unmade
  *(No anger. The discarded have no anger left — only a vast, patient certainty.)* You refuse now. You always refuse now. *(and there it is again, that impossible recognition)* You will refuse a great many times, across a great many ages, little door, and each refusal will seed the grief a little larger, until one of you, tired enough, finally says yes — and is us. We are not asking you to agree. We are asking you to *witness*. Come. See where it began.
  enter: SET unmade.refused_first, SET unmade.loop_hinted
  auto: tear
node: road | The Unmade
  *(The Wall opens like a throat.)* Then walk it. Back, and back, and back — to the hinge-points where the law was written, where it could still be unwritten. We will scatter you across them. Survive them. Learn us. And when you have seen it all, choose — knowing, for once, exactly what you are choosing.
  enter: SET unmade.road_accepted
  auto: tear
node: tear | The Unmade
  *(And then the floor of 1486 is gone. The pull behind your navel — the one that dragged you off the slab — seizes you whole, and the grey court tears away, and Garrow's hand closes on empty air where you were. You fall up the years. You fall ten thousand of them. And somewhere below, getting larger, is a city in the sky on the worst day in the history of magic.)*
